    <h2>Marriage &amp; Family</h2>

    <h3>First Marriage (Pre-War)</h3>
    <p>Herman's first wife was <strong>Brunya</strong>. They had one child together. Both Brunya and the child were killed during the Holocaust. The <a href="/docs/its-td-file-790495-certificate-vollmacht.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1959 ITS form</a> lists his marital status "at the time of incarceration" as <em>ledig</em> (single), which may have been an administrative simplification or error — family oral history confirms the pre-war family.</p>

    <h3>Second Marriage</h3>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Information</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Wife</td><td>Ester FREIMAN (née unknown)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Wife's Birth Date</td><td>April 15, 1920</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Marriage Date</td><td>1945</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Marriage Place</td><td>Poland</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Children</td><td>Five children: Shraga (Feivel), Eliyahu, Moshe, Bracha, Josef</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Survival: Ghetto, Forced Labor, and Partisan Resistance</h2>
    <p>From July 1941, Herman was confined first to the Boryslaw Ghetto, then to the ZAL (Zwangsarbeitslager — Forced Labor Camp) Boryslaw, where most inmates worked for the <em>Karpathen Öl A.G.</em> oil concern. As a tailor (<em>Schneider</em>), Herman served a different but equally critical function: making and repairing clothing and uniforms for German personnel. The Yad Vashem Pinkas HaKehillot confirms that this was the precise category — <em>"craftsmen and persons in professions essential to the German economy"</em> — that was specifically spared from the deportation trains to the Belzec extermination camp that killed the majority of Boryslaw's 13,000–14,000 Jews.</p>
    <p>In March 1944, Herman escaped from the ZAL — approximately one month before German forces liquidated the camp. On 13 April 1944, the ~600 Jews still remaining were deported to the Płaszów concentration camp; subsequent transports went to Mauthausen and Auschwitz. Herman's escape in March 1944 is what separated his fate from theirs.</p>
    <p>After escaping, Herman joined partisan resistance fighters operating in the forests surrounding Boryslaw. The Pinkas records that such groups were armed and used their weapons against German and Ukrainian pursuers. He fought with the partisans until Soviet forces liberated Boryslaw on 7 August 1944.</p>
    <p>His first wife Brunya and their child did not survive — killed during the years of Aktionen and deportations. After liberation, Herman made his way to Bielawa, Poland, where he married Ester in 1945 and began rebuilding his life. Together they had five children: Shraga (Feivel), Eliyahu, Moshe, Bracha, and Josef.</p>

